ence, his government’s social and economic policies, its foreign policy, as well as assessing the charges of authoritarianism brought against him. Written in clear, accessible prose, the book carries debate beyond current polarised views on the Venezuelan president, to consider the prospects of the new Bolivarian model surviving beyond its leader and progenitor, Hugo Chávez.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPresidentsxVenezuela. 0aPresidentszVenezuela. 4aInternational Relations 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aHugo Chávez.  aLatin America.  aStructural Adjustment Programmes.  aVenezuela.  aauthoritarianism.  ademocracy.  aforeign policy.  aglobalisation.  apopulism.1 aCannon, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779276140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792761423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792761/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles